<H2>Constraint Solving</H2>

More a technique than an application, geometric constraint solving
consists of finding configurations of points, lines, circles,
and other geometric figures constrained to have certain relations to
each other.  This sort of problem finds applications in a number of areas
including
<A HREF="cad.html">computer aided design</A>,
<A HREF="molmod.html">molecular modeling</A>,
and <A HREF="robot.html">robot motion planning</A>.
<P><UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.purdue.edu/homes/cmh/electrobook/intro.html">An
Electronic Primer on Geometric Constraint Solving</A>,
Christoph Hoffmann, Purdue.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.washington.edu/research/projects/weird/www/index.html">U. Washington Constraint-Based Languages and Systems</A>
<P>
</UL><HR><P>
